important part of all.

131
00:05:38,629 --> 00:05:42,589
No one was with her
when she died."

132
00:05:42,675 --> 00:05:46,465
(crying)

133
00:05:46,554 --> 00:05:49,394
Come on, Janey!
Everybody has a talent.

134
00:05:49,474 --> 00:05:51,314
I want to see yours.
That's all.

135
00:05:51,392 --> 00:05:53,692
-I don't have a talent.
-You can not talk like that.

136
00:05:53,770 --> 00:05:56,980
There has to be something that
you can do better than anybody else.

137
00:05:57,065 --> 00:05:59,645
Well, I can do this.

138
00:05:59,734 --> 00:06:01,444
Yes! Great.

139
00:06:01,527 --> 00:06:03,647
Okay. How about you, Ralph?

140
00:06:03,738 --> 00:06:05,698
Wonderful! Chuck.

141
00:06:07,325 --> 00:06:09,865
Oh, that's disgusting.
I love it.

142
00:06:09,952 --> 00:06:11,952
Lisa! Come on,
you're holding out on us.

143
00:06:12,038 --> 00:06:14,328
-I see a saxophone over there.
-I can't.

144
00:06:14,415 --> 00:06:16,165
Come on, Lisa.
I bet you're good.

145
00:06:16,250 --> 00:06:17,290
No, really, I can't.

146
00:06:17,377 --> 00:06:18,957
Sure, you can.
Just try.

147
00:06:19,045 --> 00:06:20,415
Please don't make me do it.

148
00:06:20,505 --> 00:06:22,255
All right, you owe me
something special.

149
00:06:22,340 --> 00:06:23,880
(bell ringing)

150
00:06:23,966 --> 00:06:25,586
(laughing and chattering)

151
00:06:27,595 --> 00:06:30,805
So... while I'm technically
still married,

152
00:06:30,890 --> 00:06:32,850
there really hasn't been
any marriage to speak of

153
00:06:32,934 --> 00:06:36,524
since Mister Krabappel moved
into his little love nest.

154
00:06:36,604 --> 00:06:39,574
This profession can put
a lot of strain on a marriage.

155
00:06:39,649 --> 00:06:41,069
Since he's been gone,

156
00:06:41,150 --> 00:06:43,030
I've been looking
for a substitute

157
00:06:43,111 --> 00:06:45,661
to teach me a lesson
I sorely need.

158
00:06:45,738 --> 00:06:48,368
Mrs. Krabappel,
you're trying to seduce me.

159
00:06:48,449 --> 00:06:49,829
(chuckles)
Well?

160
00:06:49,909 --> 00:06:51,829
I'm sorry,
Mrs. Krabappel.

161
00:06:51,911 --> 00:06:55,001
You're very nice,
but it's the children I love.

162
00:06:55,081 --> 00:06:56,621
(sighing)

163
00:06:56,707 --> 00:06:58,167
Oh...

164
00:07:00,670 --> 00:07:04,090
(saxophone playing the blues)

165
00:07:21,858 --> 00:07:23,278
When I fall asleep,

166
00:07:23,359 --> 00:07:25,069
Mr. Bergstrom is
the last thing I think of.

167
00:07:25,153 --> 00:07:26,903
And he's my first thought
when I wake up.

168
00:07:26,988 --> 00:07:28,818
I feel that way
about your father.

169
00:07:28,906 --> 00:07:30,776
No, no. You don't understand.

170
00:07:30,867 --> 00:07:33,787
When Mr. Bergstrom smiles,
you only see these teeth.

171
00:07:33,870 --> 00:07:36,000
But when you really make him laugh,
you can see these two teeth.

172
00:07:36,080 --> 00:07:37,750
I think they're called
the eye teeth?

173
00:07:37,832 --> 00:07:39,922
I don't know if he had
orthodontic work or what,

174
00:07:40,001 --> 00:07:41,591
but they're absolutely perfect.

175
00:07:41,669 --> 00:07:44,339
I notice little things
about your father too.

176
00:07:44,422 --> 00:07:46,672
No, Mom. This is different.

177
00:07:46,757 --> 00:07:49,177
I mean, this man makes you feel
like there's nobody better.

178
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:51,050
Your father does that to me.

179
00:07:51,137 --> 00:07:53,257
Mom, are we going to talk,
or are we going to talk?

180
00:07:53,347 --> 00:07:55,927
Lisa, we can talk, but first you have
to accept the fact

181
00:07:56,017 --> 00:07:58,597
-that I feel that way about your father.
-Fine.

182
00:07:58,686 --> 00:08:01,226
Yesterday he read us
"Charlotte's Web"

183
00:08:01,314 --> 00:08:03,984
and cried at the end,
never trying to hide his tears.

184
00:08:04,066 --> 00:08:08,106
-(laughing)
-(laughing)

185
00:08:08,196 --> 00:08:10,236
A book made him cry?

186
00:08:10,323 --> 00:08:12,453
-Boo-hoo!
-Waaaah!

187
00:08:12,533 --> 00:08:14,743
(groaning)

188
00:08:14,827 --> 00:08:17,707
Mr. Bergstrom: Remember,
nobody, and I mean nobody

189
00:08:17,788 --> 00:08:20,168
gets back in after lunch
without one igneous rock--

190
00:08:20,249 --> 00:08:21,789
that's volcanic--

191
00:08:21,876 --> 00:08:23,536
and one sedimentary,
and that is layered.

192
00:08:23,628 --> 00:08:25,168
Lisa, can I see you
for a minute?

193
00:08:25,254 --> 00:08:27,424
Yes! Yes, Mr. Bergstrom?

194
00:08:27,507 --> 00:08:30,217
Lisa, your homework is always so neat.
How can I put this?

195
00:08:30,301 --> 00:08:32,301
Does your father
help you with it?

196
00:08:32,386 --> 00:08:34,636
No. Homework's
not my father's specialty.

197
00:08:34,722 --> 00:08:36,222
Well, there's no shame in it.
I mean, my Dad--

198
00:08:36,307 --> 00:08:37,767
-Not mine.
-You didn't let me finish.

199
00:08:37,850 --> 00:08:39,100
Unless the next word
was "burp, "

200
00:08:39,185 --> 00:08:41,185
you didn't have to.

201
00:08:41,270 --> 00:08:44,110
In a sample taken
in this very classroom,

202
00:08:44,190 --> 00:08:49,150
a state inspector found 1.74 parts
per million of asbestos!

203
00:08:49,237 --> 00:08:52,317
That's not enough.
We demand more asbestos.

204
00:08:52,406 --> 00:08:54,366
More asbestos!
More asbestos!

205
00:08:54,450 --> 00:08:56,450
(kids chanting)
More asbestos! More asbestos!

206
00:08:56,536 --> 00:08:58,956
(camera shutter clicks)

207
00:08:59,038 --> 00:09:01,578
Wow! You made the front page.

208
00:09:01,666 --> 00:09:03,456
Aw, Dad, it's just
a popularity contest.

209
00:09:03,543 --> 00:09:05,923
Just a popularity contest?

210
00:09:06,003 --> 00:09:08,843
Excuse me, what's more
important than popularity?

211
00:09:08,923 --> 00:09:11,343
Now, Bart, do you really
think you can win?

212
00:09:11,425 --> 00:09:13,385
-Sure. Why not?
-Whoo-whoo!

213
00:09:13,469 --> 00:09:15,719
All right. I always knew
you had personality.

214
00:09:15,805 --> 00:09:18,385
The doctor said it was hyperactivity
but I knew better.

215
00:09:18,474 --> 00:09:20,354
President Simpson.

216
00:09:20,434 --> 00:09:23,194
Has a nice ring to it,
doesn't it, boy?

217
00:09:23,271 --> 00:09:24,521
Hmm... yeah.

218
00:09:24,605 --> 00:09:27,725
-Now, go get 'em!
-(growling)

219
00:09:27,817 --> 00:09:30,107
He says there aren't
any easy answers.

220
00:09:30,194 --> 00:09:32,954
I say he's not looking
hard enough!

221
00:09:33,030 --> 00:09:36,660
(kids cheering)

222
00:09:36,742 --> 00:09:39,542
(kids chanting)
Bart! Bart! Bart! Bart!

223
00:09:46,502 --> 00:09:47,552
(laughing)

224
00:09:47,628 --> 00:09:49,588
(cheering)

225
00:09:49,672 --> 00:09:52,972
(kids chanting)
Bart! Bart! Bart! Bart!

226
00:09:59,223 --> 00:10:00,773
(kids cheering)

227
00:10:00,850 --> 00:10:02,770
(sighs)
Oh, you'll never go broke

228
00:10:02,852 --> 00:10:04,442
appealing to the lowest
common denominator.

229
00:10:04,520 --> 00:10:06,150
You're gonna miss
your brother's antics.

230
00:10:06,230 --> 00:10:08,150
-When?
-When? When your life takes you places

231
00:10:08,232 --> 00:10:10,402
the rest of us
have only heard about.

232
00:10:10,484 --> 00:10:12,744
{\an8}Places where my intelligence will be
an asset and not a liability?

233
00:10:12,820 --> 00:10:15,620
Yes. There is such a place.
Believe me, it's true.

234
00:10:15,698 --> 00:10:17,368
I believe everything you say

235
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:19,490
with your words,
your body language,

236
00:10:19,577 --> 00:10:21,407
and your Semitic good looks.

237
00:10:21,495 --> 00:10:24,495
"Dear Miss Hoover,
You have lyme disease.

238
00:10:24,582 --> 00:10:25,922
"We miss you.

239
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:27,130
"Kevin's biting me.

